{"id":"1710.01472","submitter":"Ralph Keusch","authors":"Ralph Keusch","title":"A new upper bound on the game chromatic index of graphs","comments":"17 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the two-player game where Maker and Breaker alternately color the\nedges of a given graph $G$ with $k$ colors such that adjacent edges never get\nthe same color. Maker's goal is to play such that at the end of the game, all\nedges are colored. Vice-versa, Breaker wins as soon as there is an uncolored\nedge where every color is blocked. The game chromatic index $\\chi'_g(G)$\ndenotes the smallest $k$ for which Maker has a winning strategy.\n  The trivial bounds $\\Delta(G) \\le \\chi_g'(G) \\le 2\\Delta(G)-1$ hold for every\ngraph $G$, where $\\Delta(G)$ is the maximum degree of $G$. In 2008, Beveridge,\nBohman, Frieze, and Pikhurko proved that for every $\\delta>0$ there exists a\nconstant $c>0$ such that $\\chi'_g(G) \\le (2-c)\\Delta(G)$ holds for any graph\nwith $\\Delta(G) \\ge (\\frac{1}{2}+\\delta)v(G)$, and conjectured that the same\nholds for every graph $G$. In this paper, we show that $\\chi'_g(G) \\le\n(2-c)\\Delta(G)$ is true for all graphs $G$ with $\\Delta(G) \\ge C \\log v(G)$. In\naddition, we consider a biased version of the game where Breaker is allowed to\ncolor $b$ edges per turn and give bounds on the number of colors needed for\nMaker to win this biased game.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 4 Oct 2017 06:16:30 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 24 Oct 2017 12:27:38 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 7 Nov 2017 20:13:24 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 13 Feb 2018 12:39:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-14"}
